1.2 Degrees vs Radians
It’s important to discuss the units we use when measuring angles. Angles can be expressed in degrees or radians. In math, radians are preferred since they are a “natural” unit in the sense that they are directly related to the geometry of a circle. Instead of breaking up a circle into 360 arbitrary units, we can measure angles using the circle’s own radius. Here is the formula to better visualize this concept: \[
\text{Radian} = \frac{\text{distance traveled}}{\text{radius}}
\] Imagine you are riding on a carousel and sitting on a horse that is 10 meters from the center of the ride. You can figure out the angle of your rotation by dividing how many meters you have traveled in a circle (i.e., arc length) by 10 meters. You are left with a dimensionless unit (since dividing meters by meters cancels out) whose value describes the angle in radians.
To convert from degrees to radians, where \(\theta\) is an angle; \[
\theta\cdot\frac{\pi}{180°}
\] To convert from radians to degrees: \[
\theta\cdot\frac{180°}{\pi}
\]

2.1 The Reciprocal Functions
In the previous section, we introduced the three primary trigonometric functions: sine, cosine, and tangent. In this section, we introduce their reciprocals cosecant, secant, and cotangent. Once we establish these six fundamental functions we can explore the key identities that relate all six functions to one another and to the pythagorean theorem. These identities will become indispensable tools in your toolkit, particularly when we get to integration, so take special care to familiarize yourself with them.
The remaining three trigonometric functions are secant, cosecant, and cotangent and are reciprocals of the three primary functions sine, cosine, and tangent. They are defined as follows: \[
\sec\theta = \dfrac{1}{\cos} = \dfrac{1}{\frac{\text{adj}}{\text{hyp}}}=\dfrac{\text{hyp}}{\text{adj}}
\] \[
\csc\theta = \dfrac{1}{\sin} = \dfrac{1}{\frac{\text{opp}}{\text{hyp}}}=\dfrac{\text{hyp}}{\text{opp}}
\] \[
\cot\theta = \dfrac{1}{\tan} = \dfrac{1}{\frac{\text{opp}}{\text{adj}}}=\dfrac{\text{adj}}{\text{opp}}
\]
